{{Other uses|Sound Factory (disambiguation){{!}}Sound Factory}}
'''The Sound Factory''' (also known as '''Sunset Sound Factory''') is a recording studio in [[Los Angeles, California]].

The Sound Factory was built in the 1960s on Selma Avenue in Hollywood. At the time, it served as the home of [[Moonglow Records]] and the Moonglow Recording Studio.<ref> [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=biAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA18&ots=ktfef_ABtU&dq=Moonglow%20Records%20record%20label%20-wikipedia%20selma&pg=PA18#v=onepage&q=Moonglow%20Records%20record%20label%20-wikipedia%20selma&f=false News of the World] Billboard. Bob Kirstein. 05/12/64. Vol. 76, No. 49. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref> In 1969, former [[RCA]] recording engineer and [[Warner Brothers|Warner]]/[[Reprise Records|Reprise]] producer, [[David Hassinger]] purchased the Moonglow Records/Studio building and renamed it The Sound Factory.<ref name="AMI">[https://www.audiomediainternational.com/recording/recording-equipment-from-las-the-sound-factory-available-on-reverbcom Recording equipment from LA's The Sound Factory] Audio Media International. Colby Ramsey. 08/01/18. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref> The studio became one of the most popular recording studios in [[Hollywood]], which led its owner to open a second Sound Factory studio in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]]. The West Hollywood studio was eventually closed.

In November 1981, [[Sunset Sound Recorders]] owners [[Paul Camarata|Paul]] and [[Tutti Camarata]] purchased the famous studio.<ref name="AMI"/>

The Sound Factory has been used by many top music artists including [[Linda Ronstadt]]<ref name="AMI"/> (who recorded most of her career-defining hits there), [[Gram Parsons]] and [[The Flying Burrito Brothers]]<ref name="AMI"/> (in early 1970, for their 'no nonsense' country album; some of these tracks surfaced on [[Sleepless Nights (Gram Parsons album)|Sleepless Nights]]), [[Ringo Starr]], [[Dolly Parton]], [[Oingo Boingo]], [[Brian Wilson]], [[The Jackson 5]], [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Borchardt]]{{dn|date=October 2017}}, [[Keziah Jones]], [[LostProphets]], [[Jinx Titanic]], [[The Vines (band)|The Vines]], and [[Harry Chapin]].<ref name="AMI"/>

